@weirdan while I see *some* value in restricting to interfaced API, I thing it does more damage than what it brings to the table.

IMO this implementation is incorrect.

https://psalm.dev/r/ea9bd56925

```php
/** @psalm-immutable */
interface ImmutableCollection {
  /** @return mixed */
  public function get(string $key);
}

interface MutableCollection extends ImmutableCollection {
  /** @param mixed $value */
  public function set(string $key, $value): void;
}

class Collection implements MutableCollection {
  /** @return mixed */
  public function get(string $key) {
    return null;
  }  
  
  /** @param mixed $value */
  public function set(string $key, $value): void {}
}
```

> ERROR: MissingImmutableAnnotation - 14:7 - ImmutableCollection is marked immutable, but Collection is not marked immutable

As @weirdan mentioned, Psalm should make sure that all the methods contained in the interface don't mutate the objects state. The class as a whole doesn't necessarily need to be immutable.

Yeah, for example here: https://psalm.dev/r/5c66c3b907

```php
/** @psalm-pure */
function thinksItsPure(ImmutableCollection $c) : int {
  return $c->get("hello");
}

echo thinksItsPure(new Collection());
```

For now I've changed it so that immutability is only enforced on interface methods:

```php
/** @psalm-immutable */
interface Money {
     public function gimme() : int;
}

final class MyMoney implements Money {
    private int $amount = 0;
    public function gimme() : int
    {
        return $this->amount;
    }
    public function increment() : void
    {
        $this->amount += 1;
    }
}

/** @psalm-immutable */
class MyBankAccount {
    private Money $money; // problem: my bank account is now mutable
    public function __construct(Money $money) {
     	$this->money = $money;
       
       	if ($money instanceof MyMoney) {
            $money->increment(); // this is an error
       	}
    }
}
```

