@Ocramius if you can poke holes in that, happy to go back to the more strict version

@muglug the idea of immutability on objects is to avoid any by-ref mutation of state: having mutators on anything that is expected to be immutable is pretty much defeating the use of this annotation on supertypes.

@iluuu1994 yes, spooky action at a distance is very common, and effectively to be avoided.

I think folks in the thread are confusing immutability with API purity: the API declared on an interface may well be pure, but immutability is something that affects all state of an instance.

In practice, `@immutable` should be enforced on all API and state even on an interface without any method.
